const faqs = [
  { q: "GE Profile vs GE Café vs GE Monogram — where does Profile sit?", a: "Three distinct tiers within GE Appliances' wall oven lineup. <b>GE Monogram</b> — ultra-luxury $5-25k tier with Statement Collection + Advantium tri-tech; competes with Sub-Zero/Wolf and Miele. <b>GE Café</b> — style-first premium $2.5-8k tier with Matte Black/White finishes + customizable handle hardware; competes with Samsung Bespoke and LG STUDIO at aesthetic positioning. <b>GE Profile</b> (this page) — feature-focused premium $1.5-5k tier with True European Convection + SmartHQ Wi-Fi + Air Fry as the technology differentiators; competes with Samsung + LG + KitchenAid at the premium consumer tier. All three lines route parts through Haier-owned GE Appliances distribution in Louisville Kentucky. For LA customers, Profile positions as the practical-feature-rich premium wall oven rather than the aesthetic or luxury positioning of the siblings." },
  { q: "What's True European Convection?", a: "True European Convection is GE's nomenclature for a third-element convection system — the convection cavity has a dedicated heating element surrounding the convection fan (the \"third element\" beyond bake + broil), which heats the circulating air directly rather than relying on heat transfer from the main bake element. The European designation reflects the approach's origin in European premium ovens where third-element convection is standard on higher-end models. For cooking performance, True European Convection gives more even heat distribution + consistent browning across multi-rack cooking versus simple convection (fan-only without dedicated third element). Service implications: Profile True European Convection has two elements that can fail (main bake + third convection element) plus the convection fan motor, versus single-element bake in simpler ovens. Third-element failure is distinct from bake-element failure and requires its own diagnostic." },
  { q: "SmartHQ Wi-Fi + Air Fry — what's the service reality?", a: "SmartHQ is GE's Wi-Fi + app integration platform — remote cycle monitoring, firmware updates, recipe coordination, basic cook-program management from the SmartHQ app. Air Fry is a cooking mode, not a separate hardware category — the oven's convection system runs at high-speed + high-temp settings to achieve air-fryer-style crispy cooking results using the existing convection hardware. Common service scenarios: SmartHQ Wi-Fi drops after router firmware updates (network-side fix), SmartHQ app pairing lost after control-board firmware updates (re-pair sequence), Air Fry mode fails to reach temperature (underlying convection element or fan issue), Air Fry cycle aborts (thermal sensor drift or firmware bug). Most SmartHQ issues resolve at firmware + connectivity layer $180-$320 without hardware replacement. Air Fry faults usually trace to underlying convection hardware — true service repair rather than smart-feature-specific work." },
  { q: "What does GE Profile wall oven repair cost in LA?", a: "Residential diagnostic is $89, waived when you authorize the repair. GE Profile wall oven service at premium-tier pricing below luxury Monogram: bake element $280-$460; third-element (True European Convection) $320-$520; convection fan motor $360-$580; control board $440-$760; temperature sensor $240-$380; door hinge $280-$440; door glass $380-$620; thermostat $300-$480; SmartHQ firmware + connectivity reset $180-$320; self-clean door-lock motor $240-$400; self-clean thermal sensor $220-$360; double wall oven per-cavity service $380-$680. Haier Louisville Kentucky distribution typical 2-4 days common Profile parts, 3-5 days specialty current-generation components." }
];

